# State Synchronization Standards

This document defines standards for multiplayer network synchronization: authoritative server model, client prediction, rollback, and bandwidth optimization.

---

## Authoritative Server Model

### Principle

The server is the single source of truth for game state. Clients send inputs; the server validates, applies, and broadcasts state updates.

```
Client A: Input -> Server
Client B: Input -> Server
Server: Validate -> Apply -> Broadcast State
Clients: Receive State -> Render
```

### Server Responsibilities

| Responsibility | Description |
|----------------|-------------|
| Input validation | Reject invalid or impossible inputs |
| State simulation | Run game logic, physics, collision |
| Anti-cheat | Detect impossible states, speed hacks |
| Tick authority | Define simulation tick rate |
| State broadcast | Send state to clients at defined rate |

### Client Responsibilities

| Responsibility | Description |
|----------------|-------------|
| Input capture | Send user input to server |
| Prediction | Simulate locally for responsiveness |
| Interpolation | Smooth display of received state |
| Reconciliation | Correct prediction when server state arrives |

---

## Client Prediction

### Purpose

Predict local player movement immediately without waiting for server round-trip. Reduces perceived latency.

### Implementation

1. Client applies input locally and renders predicted state
2. Client sends input to server
3. Server processes input, broadcasts state
4. Client receives server state; if different, reconcile

### Prediction Rules

- [ ] Only predict local player (or entities player controls)
- [ ] Prediction uses same logic as server (deterministic)
- [ ] Store input history for reconciliation
- [ ] Server state overrides prediction when received
- [ ] Non-predictable entities use interpolation only

### Prediction Buffer

Keep last N inputs for rollback. N >= round-trip time in ticks.

```cpp
struct InputFrame {
    uint32_t tick;
    InputState input;
};
std::deque<InputFrame> input_history;
```

---

## Rollback and Reconciliation

### When Server State Arrives

1. Compare server state to predicted state at same tick
2. If match: prediction was correct; discard older inputs
3. If mismatch: rollback to server state, re-apply inputs from that tick forward

### Rollback Process

```
Server state at tick T arrives
  -> If predicted state at T matches: OK
  -> If not: Set state = server state at T
           -> Re-apply inputs for T+1, T+2, ... to current tick
           -> Re-simulate physics, collision, etc.
```

### Determinism Requirement

Rollback only works if client and server produce identical results for same inputs. Any non-determinism causes divergence and visible correction (rubber-banding).

- [ ] Fixed-point or deterministic float for physics
- [ ] Same random seed per tick
- [ ] No platform-specific behavior in simulation
- [ ] Lockstep or server-authoritative with deterministic client

